[3] North Carolina: skunk, dog, human exposure
Date: Tue 19 Apr 2022 06:37 EDT
Source: Courier-Tribune [edited]
https://eu.courier-tribune.com/story/news/2022/04/19/fourth-rabies-case-davidson-county-has-officials-warning-public-to-stay-vigilant/7358400001/


Davidson County's Health Department is advising caution following the 4th confirmed rabies bite in as many months. Earlier in the month [April 2022], the Health Department responded to a call about an animal bite. According to reports, an infected skunk found its way into an enclosure and bit 2 domestic dogs. The owner of the dogs killed the skunk. The incident occurred around the Hedrick Grove area, near US Highway 64 E.

The owner of the dogs kept them current on their rabies vaccination. Instead of euthanizing, both dogs received rabies boosts and are currently being held under a 45-day quarantine. The owner is also receiving ongoing treatment. [This implies the owner was bitten or scratched by the skunk or possibly had skunk salvia in an eye or a cut. - Mod.TG]

According to the Health Department's report, wildlife, namely skunks, foxes, and raccoons, are most active this time of year, the between weeks separating winter and spring. "Humans must also proceed with caution," advises Davidson County's Health Department. "Never touch a dead wild animal with your bare hands." Should contact occur, you are advised to not wait before seeking medical help.

Pet owners should also be vigilant. The health department warns that owners of pets must keep their animals up-to-date with their rabies vaccinations. Pet owners should also have access to a veterinarian in the case there is contact between pets and affected wildlife. Veterinarians may need to give pets a booster shot.

[Byline: Dean-Paul Stephens]

