[There are some outstanding notations in this rabies report. We rarely hear of an anteater acquiring rabies, or 13 laboratory individuals taking post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) against rabies. Those working in diagnostic laboratories and most state labs are required to have preventative rabies vaccination.

We are saddened to learn of deaths in Brazil from the hematophagous bat, which is often a vampire bat and a transmitter of rabies.

Regardless of the country you live in, or travel too, being aware of bats is paramount to survival. Bats can bite a person in their sleep and never awaken the individual. Check the rooms you use to make sure screens are on the windows. Also, if you are not familiar with the room, check closets and behind heavy pieces of furniture and chimneys for bats. If you find bats in the dwelling, it is not wise to remain there.

Any time an animal is not following what is normal for the animal, it should trigger an alert in you. Rabies can make normally aggressive animals appear shy and reserved, or a normal animal seem aggressive. While we have compassion for frightened animals, we need be extremely cautious and aware of the possibility of rabies.

Build a barrier between yourself and rabies by vaccinating your animals according to the recommendations of your veterinarian. Keep your pets up to date on their vaccinations, as they could be bitten by a rabid animal, and being up to date on their rabies vaccination could help keep them safe and alive as well. Losing our pets to this disease because of our carelessness of not keeping a pet's vaccination up to date can be a hard dose of reality I hope you do not have to experience. - Mod.TG

